The Macedonians vote in a referendum on changing the name of the country.
The Macedonian people voted on Sunday in a referendum whether they wanted to change their name to the Republic of North Macedonia, a move that would resolve a decades-old dispute with Greece and block applications for admission into the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which has a province called Macedonia, maintains that the name of its northern neighbors represents a claim to its territory and has vetoed its entry into NATO and the EU.
The governments of the two countries reached an agreement in June on the proposed new name, but nationalist opponents claim that the change would harm the ethnic identity of the majority of Macedonia's Slavic population.
President Gjorge Ivanov said he would not vote in the referendum and a boycott campaign raised doubts about whether the result would reach the minimum 50 percent needed for the referendum to be valid.
The question on the ballot was: "Are you in favour of NATO and EU membership with the acceptance of the agreement with Greece?
Advocates of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that it is a price to pay for admission to entities such as the EU or NATO of Macedonia, one of the emerging countries after the fall of Yugoslavia.
"Today I came to vote for the future of the country, for the youth of Macedonia, so that they can live freely under the protection of the European Union, because that means a safer life for all of us", said Olivera Georgijevska, 79, in Skopje.
Although it is not legally binding, several members of parliament have said they would respect the outcome of the vote and make it final.
The change of nine would require a two-thirds majority of parliament.
The state election commission said no irregularities had been reported as of 1 p.m.
However, turnout was only 16 percent, compared to 34 percent in the last parliamentary election in 2016, when 66 percent of registered voters cast their ballots.
"I came to vote for my children, our place is in Europe", said Gjose Tanevski, a 62-year-old voter from the capital, Skopje.
The Macedonian Prime Minister, Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and his son Dushko deposited their vote for the Macedonian referendum on the country's name change that would pave the way for its accession to the European Union in Strumica, Macedonia, on September 30, 2018.
In front of the parliament in Skopje, 54-year-old Vladimir Kavardarkov was setting a small stage and putting chairs in front of the tents set up for those boycotting the referendum.
"We are in favour of joining NATO and the EU, but we want to do it with our heads high and not through the service door", Kavadarkov added.
We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If we are not accepted as Macedonia, we can go to other countries like China and Russia and join the Eurasian Union.
Prime Minister Zaev says NATO membership will bring much-needed investment to Macedonia, which has an unemployment rate of over 20 percent.
"I think the vast majority will be in favour because more than 80 percent of our citizens are in favour of EU and NATO membership", Zaev said after casting his vote.
He said a positive outcome would be the "confirmation of our future".
A poll published last Monday by the Macedonian Institute for Political Research revealed that between 30 and 43 percent of voters would participate in the referendum, a figure that is below the requirement.
Another poll by the Macedonian television channel Telma indicated that 57 percent of those polled planned to vote on Sunday.
