The 31-year-old actor has attacked the stereotype of a male hero, saying that those roles on screen mean it seems that young people often have to be tough to be respected.
Speaking to The Sunday Times Culture, Kit said "something went wrong" and wondered how to address the problem of toxic masculinity in the #MeToo era.
Kit, who recently married Game of Thrones co-star Rose Leslie, also 31, admitted that she feels "strong enough" to address the issue.
"Personally, I feel pretty strong right now. What are we wrong with masculinity in?" he said.
"What do we teach men when they grow up, in terms of the problem we see now?"
Kit believes that television can be partly responsible for the increase in toxic masculinity thanks to its highly masculine characters.
He continued: "What is innate and what is taught?
What is taught on television and on the streets; what makes young people feel they have to be that certain part of being a man?
I think it's really one of the big questions of our time; how do we change that?
Because clearly something went wrong with the boys".
In the interview, he also admitted that he will not be making any prequels or sequels to Game of Thrones when the series comes to an end next summer, stating that "enough of horses and battlefields".
Starting in November, Kit will star in a remake of Sam Shepard's True West, which tells the story of a film producer and his brother, who is a thief.
Recently, the actor revealed that he considers his encounter with his wife, Rose, to be the best of Game of Thrones.
"I met my wife on this program, so in a way, it provided me with my future family and my life from now on", he said.
Rose played Ygritte, the love of Kit's character Jon Snow, in the Emmy-winning fantasy series.
The couple married in June 2018 on the land of Leslie's family estate in Scotland.
HIV/AIDS: China reports a 14% increase in new cases
China has announced a 14 percent increase in the number of citizens living with HIV or AIDS.
It affects more than 820,000 people in the country, health officials said.
40,000 new cases were reported in the second quarter of 2018 alone.
The vast majority of new cases have been sexually transmitted, which marks a change from the past.
Traditionally, HIV spread rapidly through parts of China as a result of infected blood transfusions.
However, the number of people infected with HIV in this way is reduced to almost zero, Chinese health authorities said at a conference in Yunnan province.
However, in terms of annual growth, the number of people living with HIV or AIDS in China has increased by 100,000.
Sexual transmission of HIV is a serious problem in the LGBT community in China.
Homosexuality was discriminated against in China in 1997, but they say discrimination against LGBT people has spread.
Because of the country's conservative values, studies estimate that between 70 and 90 percent of men who have sex with other men will eventually marry women.
Many of the transmission of the disease comes from inadequate sexual protection in these relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has promised universal access to mediation for HIV as part of an effort to address the problem.
Maxine Waters denies that a staff member leaked data from Republican Senators, "dangerous lies" and "conspiracy theories".
On Saturday, U.S. Representative Maxine Waters denounced allegations that a member of her staff had posted personal information of three U.S. Republican Party senators on the legislators' Wikipedia pages.
The Los Angeles Democrat said the statements were being made by "ultra-right" websites and commentators.
"Lies, lies and more infamous lies", Waters commented in a statement on Twitter.
The information reportedly included the private addresses and phone numbers of U.S. Senators Lindsey Graham of South Carolina and Mike Lee and Orrin Hatch of Utah.
The information was posted online Thursday by an unknown person on Capitol Hill, the seat of the United States government, during a Senate panel hearing on allegations of sexual misconduct against Supreme Court nominee Brett Kavanaugh.
The leak came shortly after the three senators had questioned Kavanaugh.
Conservative sites, such as Gateway Pundit and RedState, reported that the IP address identifying the origin of the publications was associated with the Waters department and disclosed information from a member of Waters staff, Capitol Hill reported.
"This baseless accusation is totally false and a complete lie", Waters continued.
"The member of my staff, whose identity, personal information and security were compromised as a result of these false and fraudulent allegations, was not responsible in any way for the leakage of this information.
This baseless accusation is completely false and a complete lie".
Waters' statement immediately drew online criticism, including that of former White House press secretary Ari Fleischer.
"This denial was made with anger", wrote Fleischer.
"He's obviously not in the mood to be a congressman.
When someone is accused of something they didn't do, you shouldn't be angry.
You must not be defiant.
You must not question the accuser's motives.
It must remain pleasant and serene".
It seemed Fleischer was comparing Waters' reaction to criticism from Judge Kavanaugh's Democrats, who critics accused of appearing too angry during Thursday's hearing.
Omar Navarro, a Republican candidate who ran to defeat Waters in the midterm elections, also expressed his opinion on Twitter.
"I'd be stronger if it was true", he shared on Twitter.
In his statement, Waters said his department has alerted "law enforcement agencies and appropriate authorities of these fraudulent allegations.
"We will make sure that the culprits are discovered", he continued, "as well as that they are legally held responsible for all their actions that are destructive and dangerous to everyone and every member of my team".
