What is the Global Citizen Festival and has it done anything to reduce poverty?
This Saturday, New York will host the Global Citizen Festival, an annual music event that features an impressive starboard set and an equally impressive mission to end global poverty.
In its seventh year, the Global Citizen Festival will see thousands of people marching to the Great Lawn of Central Park, not only to enjoy performances by Janet Jackson, Cardi B, and Shawn Mendes, but also to raise awareness of the event's real goal of ending poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival, which began in 2012, is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, an international advocacy group that hopes to end poverty by increasing the number of people actively fighting it.
In order to receive a free ticket to the event (unless you want to pay for a VIP ticket), the attending public had to complete a series of tasks or "actions", such as volunteering, emailing a world leader, making a phone call or any other meaningful way to help raise awareness about their goal of ending poverty.
But what is the success rate Global Citizen achieved 12 years after achieving its goal?
Is the idea of rewarding people with a free concert a genuine way to persuade people to ask for action or is it just another case of the so-called "cluttivism", people who think they make a difference by signing a petition online or by tweeting?
Since 2011, Global Citizen says it has recorded more than 19 million "actions" from its followers, driving a set of different goals.
He claims that these actions have helped spur world leaders to announce commitments and policies equivalent to over $37 billion set to influence the lives of over 2.25 billion people by 2030.
As of early 2018, the group cited 390 commitments and announcements derived from its stock, of which at least $10 billion has already been paid or paid off.
The group estimates that the funds secured so far have had a direct impact on nearly 649 million people worldwide.
Some of the key commitments include The Power of Nutrition, a UK-based investor and executive society committed to "helping children develop to their full potential", with a promise to provide Rwanda with $35 million to help end malnutrition in the country after receiving more than 4,700 tweets from Global Citizen.
"With the support of the UK government, donors, national authorities and Global Citizen supporters like you, we can turn the social injustice of malnutrition into a footnote in history", The Power of Nutrition ambassador Tracey Ullman told the crowd during a live concert in London in April 2018.
The group also said that after more than 5,000 actions to improve the nutrition of mothers and children in the UK, the government announced funding for The Power of Nutrition project that will reach 5 million women and children with nutrition interventions.
In response to one of the frequently asked questions on their website, "What makes you think we can end extreme poverty?"
Global Citizen responded, "It's going to be a long, hard road, and sometimes we're going to fall and fail.
But just like the great anti-apartheid and civil rights movements that preceded us, we will, because together, we are stronger.
Janet Jackson, the Weeknd, Shawn Mendes, Cardi B and Janelle Monáe are among the performers at this year's event in New York City, which will be hosted by Deborra-Lee Furness and Hugh Jackman.
