The creator of the World Wide Web wants to create a new Internet to compete with Google and Facebook.
Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, is launching a startup to compete with Facebook, Amazon, and Google.
Inrupt, the latest project of this tech legend, is a company based on Solid, Berners-Lee's open source platform.
Solid allows users to choose where to store their data and which people can access what information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee ventured out that the intent of Inrupt's crackdown is to "dominate the world".
"We have to do it", he said of the startup.
"This is a historic moment".
The app uses Solid technology to allow people to create their own "online personal data warehouse" or POD.
They may include contact lists, lists of pending tasks, calendars, music and other personal and professional tools.
It's like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack, and Spotify are all available in one browser at a time.
All of this makes this personal data warehouse unique is that the user has complete control over who can access what information.
The company calls this "personal empowerment through data".
Inrupt's idea, according to its president John Bruce, is for the company to bring the right resources, processes and skills to help make Solid available to everyone.
The company is currently made up of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security firm owned by IBM, some developers hired to work on the project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
Starting this week, developers around the world could create their own decentralized apps with the tools available on Inrupt's website.
Berners-Lee stated that neither he nor his team spoke to "Facebook nor Google about whether or not to introduce a complete change that would change their business models overnight.
"We don't need your permission".
In an article published Saturday in Medium, Berners-Lee wrote that "Inrupt's mission is to provide business energy and an ecosystem that helps protect the integrity and quality of a new Solid-based web".
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet by establishing the World Wide Web Consortium community at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has emerged as an influential voice in the debate over net neutrality.
Even during the launch of Inrupt, Berners-Lee remains the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium community, as well as the Web Foundation and Open Data Institute organizations.
"I'm very optimistic about this new age of the web", added Berners-Lee.
A tribute to Bernard Vann, a clergyman awarded the Victoria Cross in World War I
The only Church of England clergyman to be awarded the Victoria Cross during World War I received a posthumous honour in his hometown 100 years later.
Lieutenant Colonel and Reverend Bernard Vann was awarded the medal on 29 September 1918 at the attack on Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
However, he was assassinated by a sniper four days later without even knowing he had been awarded the highest British military decoration.
On Saturday, his two grandchildren were responsible for discovering a memorial in his honour at a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire.
Michael Vann, one of his grandsons, highlighted the symbolism of discovering this monument just 100 years after his grandfather's grandfather's grave that earned him the title.
According to the London Gazette, on 29 September 1918, Lieutenant-Colonel Vann led his battalion through the Saint-Quentin Channel "through a thick fog and under the yoke of intense machine gun fire".
He later rushed to the line of fire and, with "great courage", led the line forward before rushing with a cannon and without help from anyone, and shooting down three men from the enemy detachment.
Lieutenant Colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on 4 October 1918, just a month before the war ended.
Michael Vann, 72, said his grandfather's actions were "something I could never live with, but a lesson still".
He and his brother Dr James Vann also placed a wreath after the parade, which led the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Vann said he was "very honored to be part of the parade" and added that "the courage of this genuine hero demonstrates the support of so many people".
