The 24-year-old athlete claims that he didn't realize that not everyone was like him until he was in high school.
A guest on the first broadcast of Radio 4's Desert Island Discs program hosted by Lauren Laverne, he explained that he began speaking out about gay rights to give hope to others.
He also shared that being a father helped him relativize the importance of winning the Olympics.
Kirsty Young, the regular host of this show, is on sick leave.
As a guest on Laverne's first show, Daley shared that he felt " inferior " to the rest of the people because "it was socially unacceptable that you liked boys and girls".
He also said, "To this day, that feeling of inferiority and of being different is what has driven me and given me the strength to succeed".
I wanted to prove that I was "someone" so people wouldn't be disappointed when they discovered their sexuality.
With two Olympic bronze medals, she became a prominent LGBT activist and used her appearance at the Commonwealth Games of Australia to call on more countries to decriminalize homosexuality.
She decided to speak because she felt lucky to be able to live openly and without fear of repercussions, and she wanted to give hope to others.
The three-time world champion said that falling in love with American director Dustin Lance Black, whom he met in 2013, "was a complete surprise".
Daley married this Oscar winner last year and claims that the 20-year gap between them was never a problem.
"When you live so long in such a short time" (at just 14 years old, she first participated in the Olympics and her father died of cancer three years later), it's hard to find anyone your age who'd experienced similar heights.
The couple had their first child in June, Robert Ray Black-Daley, and this birth made Daley completely change his perspective.
"If you asked me last year, my biggest motivation would be to win a gold medal", he says.
"But now I know that there are things far more important than an Olympic gold medal.
For me, my medal is Robbie".
His son is named after his father Robert, who died in 2011 at age 40 from brain cancer.
Daley's father didn't accept that she was going to die, and one of the last things he asked his son to do was get tickets to London 2012, he wanted to be in the front row.
"I couldn't tell you I wouldn't be here to take that front row", Daley shared.
"I was holding his hand when he stopped breathing, and it was at that very moment, at the moment of his death, that I realized that he was not really invincible", she adds.
The following year, Daley competed at the 2012 Olympics and won a bronze medal.
"I knew at that moment that this was my life's dream: to jump in front of a crowd in my country competing in the Olympics, there was no better feeling", she confirms.
Heather Small's Proud song selection is also not in vain, as it is the tune that accompanied her during her Olympic preparation and still puts her hair on the cutting edge.
