The new German warship postponed once again
The newest frigate of the German Navy should have been delivered in 2014, to replace the old Cold War-era warships, but it will not arrive until at least next year due to faulty systems and increasing cost, local media reported.
The commissioning of the "Rheinland-Pfalz", the flagship of the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class flamboyant frigates, was postponed until the first half of 2019, a military spokesman told Die Zeit.
The ship was supposed to have been commissioned into the Marina in 2014, but problems following delivery affected the fate of this ambitious project.
The four Baden-Württemberg-class ships, commissioned by the Navy in 2007, will replace the old Bremen-class frigates.
It is understood that they will have a powerful cannon, with different anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as concealment technology such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signatures.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods, it should be possible to deploy the younger frigates up to two years outside the ports of origin.
However, as Die Zeit points out, these continuing delays mean that warships with the latest technology, which will allow Germany to project its power overseas, will be outdated when they enter service.
The unfortunate F125 frigate made headlines last year when the German Navy officially refused to commission the ship and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
It was the first time the Navy had returned a ship to a builder after delivery.
Little was known about the reasons behind this return, but German media reported "critical software and hardware defects" that prevented the warship from being used in combat missions.
The software flaws were particularly significant, as the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ships will be operated by a crew of 120 sailors; that is, half the staff needed on the old Bremen-class frigates.
Furthermore, it was discovered that the ship had a dramatic excess weight, which reduced its performance and limited the ability of the Navy to add improvements in the future.
The 7,000-ton Rheinland-Pfalz is thought to weigh twice as much as the similar class of ships used by the Germans in World War II.
In addition to the faulty hardware, the total cost of the project, which includes crew training, is also becoming a problem.
It is said to have reached the staggering 3.100 billion euros, compared with the initial 2.2 billion.
The problems of the newer frigates are of particular importance in light of recent warnings that Germany's naval power is rising.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German parliament's defence committee, acknowledged that the Marina is running out of ships fit to deploy.
The officer claims this problem is growing, as old ships have been retired, but not replaced by others.
He also regretted that none of the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates could join the Navy.
The National Trust spies on the secret lives of bats
A new study that's being conducted on a farm in the Highlands of Scotland is intended to reveal how bats use the landscape to search for food.
The results are expected to shed light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
This study led by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland association will follow the bats Pipistrellus pygmaeus and Pipistrellus pipistrellus, as well as the bats Myotis daubentonii and Plecotus auritus in the Inverewe Gardens at Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment will be placed at key locations around the property to monitor the bats' activities during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys with manual detectors.
An analysis of the sound performed by experts from all the recordings will determine the frequency of the bats' calls and what each species is doing.
Next, a habitat map will be drawn up to create a detailed landscape-scale picture of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, NTS's Nature Conservation Advisor, hopes the results will show which habitat areas are most important to bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as the creation of meadows and what is the best way to maintain forests for bats and other associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and across the UK have declined considerably over the last century.
These animals are threatened by construction and development works that affect children and habitat loss.
Air generators and hookers also pose a risk, as do fly glue traps, some chemical treatments of building materials, and domestic cat attacks.
Bats are not blind.
But because of their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when hunting.
They use a sophisticated ecolocation technique to locate insects and obstacles in their flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 gardens and 76,000 acres of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts, who conduct periodic surveys, child inspections and, in some cases, even rescue operations.
The organisation even has Scotland's only and first bat reserve at Threave Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
David Thompson, the estate manager, claims this is the ideal territory for them.
"In Threave we have a large bat area", he says.
"We have old buildings, historic trees, and a wonderful habitat.
But there are many things we don't know about bats yet, so the work we do here and in other properties will help us better understand what they need to thrive".
It stresses the importance of controlling the presence of bats before performing maintenance tasks on the property, as it is possible that the unintentional destruction of a single maternity baby could kill up to 400 females and young, which could exterminate an entire local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass or molest them, as well as to destroy their young.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish official with the Bat Conservation Trust, encourages people to help:
"There is still much to learn about bats, and in the case of many species, we don't know how their populations are doing".
