Brexit: carmakers would leave the UK
The UK would regret forever losing its position as the world's leading car manufacturer after Brexit, according to Secretary of State for Business Greg Clark.
He added that it was worrying that Toyota UK had claimed on the BBC that if Britain left the EU without a deal, it would temporarily halt production at its Burnaston factory near Derby.
"It is necessary to reach an agreement", Clark added.
The Japanese automaker has said that if Brexit does not reach any agreement, the impact of delays at the border could cost jobs.
The Burnaston plant, which manufactures Toyota's Auris and Avensis, produced around 150,000 vehicles last year, 90% of which were exported to the rest of the EU.
"In my opinion, if Britain leaves the EU at the end of March, we will be witnesses of how production stops at our factory", said Marvin Cooke, Toyota's CEO at Burnaston.
Other UK carmakers have also expressed fears of leaving the EU without reaching an agreement on the functioning of cross-border trade, including Honda, BMW and Jaguar Land Rover.
For example, BMW confirmed that it would close its Mini plant in Oxford a month after Brexit.
One of the main concerns of carmakers is the risk of the supply chain in the event of a no-deal Brexit.
Toyota's production line is highly streamlined, with customized automotive parts coming in every 37 minutes from UK and EU suppliers.
If the UK leaves the EU on 29 March without reaching an agreement, the border could be affected and delays and shortages of parts could result.
The company claims that it would be impossible for Toyota to maintain a normal pace for more than a day at the Derbyshire plant, so production would have to be stopped.
Clark claims that Theresa May's Chequers plan for future relations with the EU is "calibrated precisely to avoid such border checks".
"It's essential to have a deal. And we want it to be the best deal, so that we can enjoy the success we have now but also make the most of this opportunity", he said on BBC Radio 4's Today programme.
"The experience of Toyota and other manufacturers is that it is necessary to continue these excellent supply chains".
Toyota could not estimate how long production would be halted, but warned that in the long run the added costs would reduce the plant's competitiveness and could even cost jobs.
Peter Tsouvallaris, a 24-year Burnaston employee and Unite union coordinator, said that its members are increasingly concerned: "From experience, I know that once these jobs disappear, they never come back.
A government spokesman said they had presented a precise and credible plan for the future relationship between the UK and the EU.
Trump's meeting with Rosenstein could be delayed again
The White House has said that the high-stakes meeting of Donald Trump and Deputy Attorney General Rosenstein could be delayed by another week due to the battle for Supreme Court nominee Brett Kavanaugh.
Rosenstein oversees the work of Special Counsel Robert Mueller, who is investigating Russian election interference, ties between Russian aides and Trump, and possible obstruction of justice by the president.
Whether Trump fires the deputy attorney general or not, which would jeopardize Mueller's independence, has fueled rumors in Washington for months.
Earlier this month, The New York Times reported that Rosenstein spoke of using a microphone to record conversations with Trump and the possibility of removing the president from office under the 25th Amendment.
However, Rosenstein denied the report.
But last Monday he went to the White House, amid reports that he was about to resign.
Instead, a meeting with Trump, who was in New York on Thursday, was announced.
Trump stated that he would rather not have to fire Rosenstein, but the meeting was delayed to avoid a clash with the Senate Judiciary Committee hearing in which Kavanaugh and Christine Blasey Ford, one of the women accusing him of inappropriate sexual conduct, testified.
On Friday, Trump ordered a week-long investigation into the allegations against Kavanaugh by the FBI, which further delayed the Senate vote.
Sarah Sanders, Trump's press secretary, appeared on Fox News Sunday.
When asked about the meeting with Rosenstein, he replied, "There's no set date yet, it could be this week or it could be a week later given everything that's going on in the Supreme Court.
We'll see, but you know I like the press to be informed".
Some journalists questioned that claim, as Sanders has not held a press conference since September 10.
When host Chris Wallace asked him why,
Sanders claimed that the lack of briefing was not due to a dislike of the reporters' grandiloquence, although she added that she would not deny that attitude.
He also suggested that direct contact between Trump and the press would increase.
"The president gives more interviews than the previous president", he said, though he did not cite any sources to back up those data.
Information meetings will continue, Sanders said, but insisted that "if the press has the opportunity to ask the president of the United States directly, that's much better than asking him questions.
You're witnesses of how we've been doing this for the past few weeks, and that will replace a press conference where you can talk directly to the president of the United States".
Trump often answers questions when he leaves the White House or attends open sessions or press conferences with visiting dignitaries.
However, solo press conferences are rare.
Perhaps the president demonstrated the motive this week in New York, with a free and sometimes bizarre appearance before the press.
