A stamp duty will apply to foreign buyers who buy property in the UK
Foreign buyers will be charged a higher stamp duty when they buy a property in the UK. This additional money will be used to help homeless people under the new conservative plans.
This measure will neutralize the success of Corbyn's campaign to attract young voters.
The stamp duty increase will apply to those people who do not pay taxes in the UK
The Treasury expects to raise up to £120 million a year to help the homeless
Foreign buyers will be charged a higher stamp duty when they buy property in the UK. Theresa May will announce that this additional money will be used to help the homeless.
The move will be seen as an attempt to neutralize the success of Jeremy Corbyn's campaign to attract young voters with promises to promote more affordable housing and focus on high-income people.
The raise in the stamp duty will apply to tax-free individuals and businesses in the UK, and the money raised will support the government's campaign to reduce the number of people sleeping on the streets.
The surcharge, which is added to the current stamp duty, including the highest levels introduced two years ago for second homes and rental purchases, can be up to 3%.
The business expects the change to reach up to £120 million a year.
Approximately 13% of new construction in London is marketed by non-residents in the UK, which is causing prices to rise and making it harder for people who want to buy a home for the first time to access the housing market.
Many of the country's rich areas, especially the capital, have become "ghost towns" due to the high number of foreign buyers spending most of their time outside the country.
This new policy comes just weeks after Boris Johnson requested a reduction in estate tax to help young people acquire their first home.
He accused the big homebuilders of keeping house prices high by buying land and not using it, and urged Mrs May to remove the tax revenue percentages on moderate-priced homes to settle the "housing shame" that is being experienced in Britain.
Mr Corbyn has announced an attractive series of housing reform proposals, including rental controls and a ban on challenges where the tenant is not to blame.
He also wants to give municipalities greater powers in building new homes.
Mrs May stated: "Last year I said I would dedicate my mandate to restoring the British dream: that life should be better for every new generation.
And that's what we need to do to fix the disastrous housing market.
Britain will always be open to anyone who wants to live, work and start a life here.
However, it is not fair that it is as easy for those people who do not live in the UK as it is for foreign-based businesses to buy housing than for working British residents.
For too many people, the dream of owning a home is too far away, and the indignity of not having a roof remains too real".
Jack Ross: My last ambition is to be able to train Scotland
Sunderland manager Jack Ross has stated that his "ultimate ambition" is to become Scotland's manager at some point.
The 42-year-old Scot is enjoying the challenge of reviving the North West club, which currently sits third in League One, three points from the top.
He arrived at the Stadium of Light this summer after taking St Mirren back to the Scottish Premiership last season.
"When I was a player my dream was to play for my country.
I played once in the B team, and that was it", Ross told BBC Scotland's Sportsound.
"I grew up watching Scotland play in Hampden many times with my father as a child, something I always wanted to live again.
But that opportunity will only come if I succeed in running a club".
Ross's predecessors as Sunderland coach include Dick Advocaat, David Moyes, Sam Allardyce, Martin O'Neill, Roy Keane, Gus Poyet and Paulo Di Canio.
The former Alloa Athletic manager claims he felt no anxiety about succeeding such established figures at such a big club after previously rejecting offers from Barnsley and Ipswich Town.
"Will my success at this moment depend on whether I can bring this club back to the Premier League?
Because the structure and facilities of the club are undoubtedly owned by a Premier League club", he said.
"It won't be an easy task to get to, but I'll probably only consider that I've achieved success here if I can get the club back to the Premier".
Ross has only been coaching for three years after a stint as an assistant at Dumbarton and a 15-month stint on the Hearts technical staff.
During that period he helped Alloa recover from relegation to the third division and managed to get St Mirren from the bottom of the table to the Championship title the following season.
Ross claims to feel more comfortable now than he ever felt during his playing career at Clyde, Hartlepool, Falkirk, St Mirren and Hamilton Academical.
"I was probably at a royal crossroads", he recalled, about taking over the Alloa.
"I really thought training was perfect for me, even more so than playing.
Sounds weird because I didn't do badly, I made a reasonably good living and enjoyed some successes.
But playing can be hard.
There are a lot of things you have to get over every week.
I still suffer from the stress and the pressure of work, but I like to train.
I've always enjoyed training, and now that I'm doing it, I feel more comfortable than ever in my adult life".
