According to a survey, the perfect time to take a drink is 5:30 p.m. on a Saturday.
The summer heat wave increased consumption in British pubs with more difficulty, but put more pressure on restaurant chains.
Pubs and bars experienced 2.7 percent growth during July, but consumption in restaurants fell 4.8 percent according to the figures.
Peter Martin, member of the CGA trade advisory board, responsible for compiling the figures, said: "The slippery days and England's longer-waited stay at the World Cup caused a similar pattern to June in July, in which pubs enjoyed a 2.8 percent increase in consumption, although restaurants suffered even greater punishment.
The 1.8 percent drop in restaurant turnover in June worsened in July.
The pubs and bars specializing in beverages were the ones that achieved the best results with increases in consumption higher than the reductions experienced by restaurants.
Food-specialized pubs also suffered from the sun, though not as dramatically as restaurant operators.
It's like people just want to go out and drink.
In controlled pubs and bars, drinking increased by 6.6 percent during the month, and food consumption decreased by three percent".
Paul Newman, employee of leisure and hospitality analytics firm RSM, said: "These results are a continuation of the trend that has been occurring since late April.
The timing and impact of major social and sporting events continue to be the main factors in the consumption relationship outside the home.
It is not surprising that restaurant groups continue to suffer, however, a fall of 4.8 percent annually will be especially painful if added to this the continuing increase in costs.
The warm, long summer could not have come at a worse time for the restaurant business and time will tell whether the moderation of temperatures experienced during August will provide much needed respite for the sector".
Total sales growth in pubs and restaurants, including new openings, was 2.7 percent during July, reflecting a slowdown in brand launches.
The Coffer Peach Tracker Industry sales indicator for the UK pub, bar and restaurant sector collects and analyses performance data from 47 operating groups with combined profits of over £9bn and is considered the benchmark for the sector.
