Earthquakes and tsunamis in Indonesia
A powerful earthquake and tsunami that hit the Indonesian city of Palu on Friday, according to official sources, killed at least 384 people, a figure expected to continue to rise.
Due to the communications cut, rescue teams were unable to obtain any information from the Donggala Regency, an area located north of Palu that is closer to the epicenter of the 7.5 magnitude earthquake.
In Palu, more than 16,000 people were evacuated after the disaster.
Below we provide you with some key information about Palu and Donggala on Celebes Island:
Palu is the capital of the province of Célebes Central, which is located at the end of a narrow bay on the west coast of the island of Célebes, with a population of approximately 379,800 in 2017.
The city was celebrating its 40th anniversary when the earthquake and tsunami occurred.
Donggala is a regency located along more than 300 km of coastline in the northwest of Celebes Island.
This regency, an administrative region less than a province, had a population of approximately 299,200 in 2017.
Fisheries and agriculture are the main pillars of the economy of Central Celebes province, especially in the Donggala coastal region.
Nickel mines are also important in the province, but are mainly concentrated in Morowali, on the opposite coast of Celebes.
Palu and Donggala have been affected by tsunamis several times over the past 100 years according to the Indonesian Disaster Mitigation Agency.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes in Donggala.
A tsunami also affected the western part of Donggala in 1996, killing nine people.
Indonesia is located on the Pacific Ring of Fire with high seismic activity, so it suffers from earthquakes regularly.
These are some of the major earthquakes and tsunamis that have occurred in recent years:
2004: A major earthquake on the western coast of Indonesia's Aceh province, in northern Sumatra, that occurred on December 26, caused a tsunami that affected 14 countries, killing 226,000 people on the Indian Ocean coast, more than half of them in Aceh.
2005: A series of strong earthquakes hit the west coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Hundreds of people died on the island of Nias off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A 6.8 magnitude earthquake struck south of Java, Indonesia's most populous island, causing a tsunami that devastated the southern coast, killing nearly 700 people.
2009: A 7.6 magnitude earthquake occurred near the city of Padang, the capital of West Sumatra province.
More than 1,100 people died.
2010: A 7.5-magnitude earthquake struck the Mentawai Islands off Sumatra, causing a 10-meter-high tsunami that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A mild earthquake struck the Pidie Jaya regency in Aceh, causing destruction and panic as people recalled the devastation caused by the deadly 2004 earthquake and tsunami.
This time, there was no tsunami, but over 100 people died as a result of the collapse of buildings.
2018: Major earthquakes occurred on the Indonesian tourist island of Lombok, killing more than 500 people, most of them in the northern part of the island.
The earthquake destroyed thousands of buildings and left thousands of tourists temporarily stranded.
